Content:
The article references <a href="http://www.opensource.apple.com/source/Libc/Libc-1044.40.1/gen/fts.c" rel="nofollow">http://www.opensource.apple.com/source/Libc/Libc-1044.40.1/g...</a> but there&#x27;s nothing that particularly stands out as being the bug at a quick glance and it <i>is</i> designed to handle arbitrarily deep hierarchies; nonetheless this looks like an off-by-one to me (in fts_alloc):<p><pre><code>    len = sizeof(FTSENT) + namelen;
    if (!ISSET(FTS_NOSTAT))
        len += sizeof(struct stat) + ALIGNBYTES;
    if ((p = malloc(len)) == NULL)
        return (NULL);

    /* Copy the name plus the trailing NULL. */
    memmove(p->fts_name, name, namelen + 1);
</code></pre>
It&#x27;s a pretty minor bug, since I&#x27;d bet the chances of it causing a major exploitable vulnerability are quite low. A theoretical attacker can only control somewhat coarsely where a single byte with the value 0 can be written, and this is in userspace. Most of the time it probably lands in unused padding, and otherwise in an invalid address which causes a segfault.
